    <summary>Grave Secrets Kathy ReichsMystery isn&apos;t my normal fare, but I&apos;ve come to greatly enjoy the Temperance Brennan books by Kathy Reichs. Her writing style differs from what I&apos;m used to. Her tone is clipped to such a degree that Tempe&apos;s...</summary>
    <author>
        <name>Rob Hilton</name>
        
    </author>
    
        <category term="Books" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#category" />
    
    <category term="american" label="American" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#tag" />
    <category term="mystery" label="mystery" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#tag" />
    <category term="reviews" label="reviews" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#tag" />
    
    <content type="html" xml:lang="en" xml:base="http://blue-mage.net/blog/">
        <![CDATA[<a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0671028383?ie=UTF8&amp;tag=hilhom-20&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=390957&amp;creativeASIN=0671028383"><img alt="Grave Secrets.jpg" src="http://blue-mage.net/blog/Images/Grave%20Secrets.jpg" class="mt-image-left" style="margin: 0pt 20px 20px 0pt; float: left;" height="160" width="99" /></a><p><font style="font-size: 1.25em;"><b>Grave Secrets</b><br /> <i><font style="font-size: 0.9em;">Kathy Reichs</font><br /></i></font></p><p>Mystery isn't my normal fare, but I've come to greatly enjoy the Temperance Brennan books by Kathy Reichs. Her writing style differs from what I'm used to. Her tone is clipped to such a degree that Tempe's internal voice sounds a lot more like a computer than a narrator, which is certainly in keeping with the Brennan character on <i>Bones.</i>&nbsp;</p><p>What's surprising is that the clipped, clinical narrator may be an even better choice for presenting the tragedies in <i>Fatal Voyage</i> and <i>Grave Secrets</i> than the narrator that we're used to. As much as I'd prefer to empathize, I don't think there's any way to emotionally connect with an events so terrible. The dispassionate narration is a more effective tool in this instance as it allows the reader to comprehend the tragedy rather than connect with it emotionally. In the age of murder and forensics TV shows like <i>CSI </i>and <i>Bones</i> itself, it's become increasingly rare for death - on any magnitude - to be as traumatic. Reichs gets through the desensitization by not trying to overwhelm you emotionally.</p><p>When it comes right down to it, I enjoyed the book. The mystery was a real mystery and it was very well-written.<br /></p><p><br /></p>]]>
        
    </content>
</entry>

