    <summary> Sun of SunsKarl SchroederIt&apos;s fairly rare that I don&apos;t finish a book. It&apos;s even more rare that I give up after less than 50 pages, but that&apos;s exactly what happened with this one. At a guess, part of the...</summary>
    <author>
        <name>Rob Hilton</name>
        
    </author>
    
        <category term="Books" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#category" />
    
    <category term="canadian" label="Canadian" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#tag" />
    <category term="disappointment" label="disappointment" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#tag" />
    <category term="scifi" label="sci-fi" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#tag" />
    
    <content type="html" xml:lang="en" xml:base="http://blue-mage.net/blog/">
        <![CDATA[<a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0765354535?ie=UTF8&amp;tag=hilhom-20&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=390957&amp;creativeASIN=0765354535"><img alt="Sun of Suns.jpg" src="http://blue-mage.net/blog/Images/Sun%20of%20Suns.jpg" class="mt-image-left" style="margin: 0pt 20px 20px 0pt; float: left;" height="160" width="97" /></a> <div><font style="font-size: 1.25em;"><b>Sun of Suns</b></font><br /><font style="font-size: 0.9em;"><i>Karl Schroeder</i></font><br /><br />It's fairly rare that I don't finish a book. It's even more rare that I give up after less than 50 pages, but that's exactly what happened with this one. At a guess, part of the problem is that I saw favourable remarks about Schroeder's books on io9 and since I really enjoy making a point of reading Canadian sci-fi, I had rather high hopes, perhaps even unreasonably so.<br /><br />My biggest issue in the 50 pages I did read is that Schroeder seems to suffer from a form of gadgetitis. Few things drive me quite as batty as gadgetitis. It's what drives me up the wall with authors like Dan Simmons and Chris Moriarty. In Schroeder's case, He has this really cool idea for a premise and seems to have written a book to explain it. Problem is, in that fifty pages, it doesn't appear that the premise is integral in any way to the plot. It doesn't even make a huge amount of sense.<br /><br />A giant ball containing vast quantities of smaller planetoids moving according to no particular order? I have to wonder why anyone would be a structure of that nature and not plan out the interior more carefully. The settlements are all made out of wood. Since sunlight is considered a valuable resource, I would expect wood to be in much shorter supply. And harnessing "suns"? No comment.<br /><br />I think I had to stop reading the book simply to avoid being disappointed by a book I wanted to like.<br /></div>]]>
        
    </content>
</entry>

<entry>
    <title>So apparently, we don&apos;t need to do homework anymore...</title>
    <link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="http://blue-mage.net/blog/2009/11/so-apparently-we-dont-need-to-do-homework-anymore.html" />
    <id>tag:blue-mage.net,2009:/blog//1.16</id>

    <published>2009-11-19T03:01:40Z</published>
    <updated>2009-11-19T06:54:40Z</updated>

    <summary>I worry about the precedent this sort of thing sets. While I realize that there are a variety of learning styles and the current education system (in Calgary, which I went through) caters to a rather small subset of them,...</summary>
    <author>
        <name>Rob Hilton</name>
        
    </author>
    
        <category term="News" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#category" />
    
        <category term="Random" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#category" />
    
    <category term="education" label="education" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#tag" />
    <category term="irks" label="irks" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#tag" />
    <category term="news" label="news" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#tag" />
    
    <content type="html" xml:lang="en" xml:base="http://blue-mage.net/blog/">
        <![CDATA[I worry about the precedent <a href="http://www.cbc.ca/canada/calgary/story/2009/11/18/calgary-homework-school-students.html">this</a> sort of thing sets. While I realize that there are a variety of learning styles and the current education system (in Calgary, which I went through) caters to a rather small subset of them, I'm not sure that a no-homewok contract is really in the best interests of his children. I foresee a couple of problems here:<br /><br />1) Work Ethic<br />Face it, we're talking about kids. A large part of why we incorporate homework into the system is that we want to teach our children how to sit down at work at something. It's usually considered good preparation for a job in which you sit at a desk for eight hours a day and work. This type of setup completely misses that, and freed of the constraints of doing that homework (which was supposed to be helping them study the material they're supposed to know anyway), I'm not really sure a) how they're going to study and b) what's going to get them to actually work.<br /><br />2) Other skills<br />There are a number of skills we learn simply by doing rote work. One of the biggest is honing our ability to think analytically (a skill which many seem to lack). Sometimes, you just have to stare at and pound your head against a problem until the metaphorical light comes on. Another major skill this sidesteps is the ability to do simple calculations very quickly. One of the skills I've found the most useful in engineering is the ability to do simple arithmetic very quickly.<br /><br />The other skill I think this doesn't help is going to be their predictive capabilities. This is definitely subject for another post because I don't think schools in general do enough to teach this. By doing a variety of very similar problems we learn to recognize what the answers should be and to estimate those answers before calculating them. It allows us to recognize very quickly when we make errors and to find those errors in our calculations. But to do it, we have to know what kind of answers to expect.<br /><br />Benefits<br />Not this this plan isn't without certain advantages. I can't disagree that there is a thing as too much homework, especially in elementary and junior high. Kids really must have the time to develop their own interests and their own personalities. It's really hard to do that when you go home every day and spend the rest of the evening with your nose in a book.<br /><br />As with many things, I think this is a question of balance, and I don't think this particular plan is any more balanced than what they had before.<br /> ]]>
        
    </content>
</entry>

<entry>
    <title>The Andrews Sisters</title>
    <link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="http://blue-mage.net/blog/2009/11/the-andrews-sisters.html" />
    <id>tag:blue-mage.net,2009:/blog//1.15</id>

    <published>2009-11-18T16:38:14Z</published>
    <updated>2009-11-18T16:53:22Z</updated>

    <summary>I&apos;ve decided to ditch a class and just write for once. I&apos;m in the middle of a destress period and so I&apos;m not feeling terribly ambitious just at the moment.I spent a while yesterday looking up folk music on youtube....</summary>
    <author>
        <name>Rob Hilton</name>
        
    </author>
    
        <category term="Music" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#category" />
    
    <category term="music" label="music" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#tag" />
    <category term="oldies" label="oldies" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#tag" />
    <category term="random" label="random" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#tag" />
    
    <content type="html" xml:lang="en" xml:base="http://blue-mage.net/blog/">
        <![CDATA[I've decided to ditch a class and just write for once. I'm in the middle of a destress period and so I'm not feeling terribly ambitious just at the moment.<br /><br />I spent a while yesterday looking up folk music on youtube. I'm the product of a rather odd family and it shows. I grew up on the Kingston Trio, Peter, Paul, and Mary, Woody Guthrie and this list goes on for a really long time. The radio was permanently tuned to the oldies station (until they changed it to the 24-hour news station). In any case, I've ended enjoying a lot of culture that isn't current. Most of it was produced long before I was born and nor small amount before my parents were even around.<br /><br />In all of this, I went to check up on a little bit of trivia I'd heard once: that the artist or group with the most Billboard top 10 hits wasn't Elvis or the Beatles, but the Andrews Sisters. 46 of their songs hit top 10, more than anyone else before or after. And for the most part, my generation has never heard of them. Terribly, terribly, disappointing.<br /><br />

<object height="525" width="660"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/2pfCFU3Mqww&amp;hl=en_GB&amp;fs=1&amp;rel=0&amp;border=1" /><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true" /><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always" /><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/2pfCFU3Mqww&amp;hl=en_GB&amp;fs=1&amp;rel=0&amp;border=1" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" height="364" width="445"></object>]]>
        
    </content>
</entry>

