    <summary> Outback Stars Sandra McDonaldSpace opera the totally unglamorous way: working as an officer in Supply and Maintenance on the outer space equivalent of an aircraft carrier. Sounds boring, right? Well, it is.And that&apos;s the main issue with this book....</summary>
    <author>
        <name>Rob Hilton</name>
        
    </author>
    
        <category term="Books" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#category" />
    
    <category term="books" label="books" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#tag" />
    <category term="reviews" label="reviews" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#tag" />
    <category term="scifi" label="sci-fi" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#tag" />
    <category term="spaceopera" label="space opera" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#tag" />
    
    <content type="html" xml:lang="en" xml:base="http://blue-mage.net/blog/">
        <![CDATA[<div><a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0765355558?ie=UTF8&amp;tag=hilhom-20&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=390957&amp;creativeASIN=0765355558"><img alt="Outback_Stars.jpg" src="http://blue-mage.net/blog/Pictures/Outback_Stars.jpg" class="mt-image-right" style="margin: 0pt 0pt 20px 20px; float: right;" height="200" /></a> <p><font style="font-size: 1.25em;"><b>Outback Stars</b><br /> <i><font style="font-size: 0.72em;">Sandra McDonald</font><br /></i></font></p><p>Space opera the totally unglamorous way: working as an officer in Supply and Maintenance on the outer space equivalent of an aircraft carrier. Sounds boring, right? Well, it is.</p><p>And that's the main issue with this book. Regardless of all the exciting pieces of action in the story, it's essentially dull. Especially when the heroine has no real character flaws. She's freakishly like the Australian version of Honor Harrington. Not a good sign...</p><p>Speaking of Australia, while I understand the desire to culturally flavour a universe with one that's familiar to us in the present day, there are good ways of pulling it off and not so good ways. <i>The Outback Stars</i> seriously overdoes it. The Australian theme doesn't just flavour her universe, it completely overpowers it. When we start getting trips to the dreamworld to chat with aboriginal deities, I've got issues. And it's boring. I'm really not a fan of "trippy" sequences, especially when I'm reading, and the ones in here really ended up turning me off.</p><p>In fact, the only really interesting thing in the whole story is this interstellar transport system they stumble into, and I really, <i>really</i> hope it gets elaborated on in the next two books. Don't get me wrong, it's not a bad book. It's just nothing out of the ordinary, either.<br /></p></div>]]>
        
    </content>
</entry>

