<entry>
    <title>Book Review: Night of Knives</title>
    <link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="http://blue-mage.net/blog/2009/11/book-review-night-of-knives.html" />
    <id>tag:blue-mage.net,2009:/blog//1.11</id>

    <published>2009-11-10T05:09:42Z</published>
    <updated>2009-11-12T00:49:37Z</updated>

    <summary>Night of Knives Ian C. Esslemont I do believe this is the first time I&apos;ve read an entire novel that takes place in a single night. This is very definitely the prelude to the Malazan Book of the Fallen. I...</summary>
    <author>
        <name>Rob Hilton</name>
        
    </author>
    
        <category term="Books" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#category" />
    
    <category term="books" label="books" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#tag" />
    <category term="canadian" label="Canadian" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#tag" />
    <category term="fantasy" label="fantasy" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#tag" />
    <category term="reviews" label="reviews" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#tag" />
    
    <content type="html" xml:lang="en" xml:base="http://blue-mage.net/blog/">
        <![CDATA[<div><a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0765323710?ie=UTF8&amp;tag=hilhom-20&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=390957&amp;creativeASIN=0765323710"><img height="200" style="margin: 0pt 20px 10px 0pt; float: left;" class="mt-image-left" src="http://blue-mage.net/blog/Pictures/Night%20of%20Knives_.jpg" alt="" /></a><font style="font-size: 1.25em;"><b>Night of Knives</b></font><br />
<font style="font-size: 0.9em;"><i>Ian C. Esslemont</i></font><br />
<br />
I do believe this is the first time I've read an entire novel that takes place in a single night. This is very definitely the prelude to the Malazan Book of the Fallen. I actually started reading Gardens of the Moon right after to see how it all ties together and it's downright beautiful. The first of Erickson's books starts in the same place off the same events, years later.<br />
<br />
For anyone unfamiliar, Esslemont and Erickson are old buds and their series take place in a shared world that developed out of their roleplaying gaming. Their world, Malaz, is incredibly rich and consequently <i>very</i> hard to follow sometimes. But then again, I'm sure I'd be complaining if it was simple and easy to follow. What's important is that I really enjoy being able to read excellent Canadian sci-fi and fantasy and this totally qualifies.<br />
<br />
The short timespan may actually be the book's greatest weakness. It creates some weird pacing that doesn't feel right. and there's a lot of detail in the book that really serves very little purpose but to pad. It even shows up in the formatting: the margins are huge and even the font size is overly large. It's like a 300 page book that the editor decided absolutely had to take up 500 pages. Well, I <i>like</i> shorter novels. Brevity is always appreciated (as much difficulty as I tend to have acheiving it).<br />
<br />
Where this book has a leg up on Erickson's material is in its simplicity. There are two main characters and a limited cast of supporting characters, most of whom don't show up in the later books in the series. That makes is a lot easier to follow and also means it's an easier introduction to the main series.<br />
<br />
It's definitely an action-packed book, though much of it is in one-on-one encounters and the single larger battle that gets Kellanved and Dancer into the Deadhouse. I did find the interactions with Edgewalker to be tiresome after a while. He's very smug and mysterious. I don't mind smug and mysterious when there's a payoff, but there's really no payoff in this one.<br />
What I really want to see (since I've only read the first four books of the main series) is a way more material on Dassem Ultor and Temper.</div>]]>
        
    </content>
</entry>

