    <category term="spaceopera" label="space opera" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#tag" />
    
    <content type="html" xml:lang="en" xml:base="http://blue-mage.net/blog/">
        <![CDATA[<a href="http://blue-mage.net/blog/Images/Banks%2C%20Iain%20M.%20-%20Culture%2007%20-%20Look%20to%20Windward.jpg"><img alt="Look to Windward Cover.jpg" src="http://blue-mage.net/blog/assets_c/2009/11/Banks,%20Iain%20M.%20-%20Culture%2007%20-%20Look%20to%20Windward-thumb-364x579-3.jpg" class="mt-image-right" style="margin: 0pt 0pt 20px 20px; float: right;" height="200" /></a><font style="font-size: 1.25em;"><strong>Look to Windward</strong></font><br /><i><font style="font-size: 0.9em;">Iain M. Banks</font></i><br /><br />What an incredible book. I know space opera is supposed to be full of epic battles and massive fleets. And under that definition, <i>Look to Windward</i> probably wouldn't qualify as true space opera. But it is, and it's simultaneously so much more.<br /><br />I think what fascinates me about Banks' books is the sheer scale. The Orbitals are Dyson rings containing 50 billion people. GSVs (General Systems Vehicles) are the largest Culture ships and home to millions of people and entire cities. Even time is taken on a scale that makes human lifetimes irrelevant.<br /><br />I rather doubt that spoilers are necessary since the book has virtually no conflict. That's not to say it doesn't have a plot - it most certainly does. But the only conflict occurs almost at the very end of the book and is essentially irrelevant to the book as a whole. I've learned to trust Banks in a number of ways, and this is probably the most important. The book will be good and I can just sit back, relax and enjoy the characters until he decides to get to the point. And a space opera without a clearly defined conflict is a novel thing indeed.<br /><br />And there's another of Banks' strengths: his ability to make us look at ourselves through the eyes of some very surprising others. The Culture itself is a society so advanced I have difficulty relating to most of its members. The biggest problem is that in a post-scarcity society with nearly godlike powers, what the hell is there to do? And yet, his SC agent characters always feel balanced, well-rounded and empathetic. Many of them are even likable.<br /><br />Most of the book is actually delivered from the point of view of an alien ambassador and his conversations with the rather irritable Chelgrian composer are both pointed and amusing. What's really neat is how he puts the Chelgrians in our place and shows the actions we might take on having our society interfered with by a more advanced one. Not only is this relevant in the case of potential contact with extraterrestrials in the future, but with our treatment of third world nations or simply other cultures we don't understand really well. Islam, anyone? Suddenly, terrorism doesn't seem quite so incomprehensible.<br /><br />By the way, <i>Experiencing a Signifcant Gravitas Shortfall </i>is quite possibly the best ship name ever.<br /><br /><br />]]>
        
    </content>
</entry>

<entry>
