    <summary>In Conquest BornC.S. FriedmanI&apos;d like to start by saying that I absolutely adored In Conquest Born. It was topsy and turvy and ever so twisty. It had characters who were deep and interesting and that behaved like real (albeit rather...</summary>
    <author>
        <name>Rob Hilton</name>
        
    </author>
    
        <category term="Books" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#category" />
    
    <category term="books" label="books" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#tag" />
    <category term="disappointment" label="disappointment" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#tag" />
    <category term="fantasy" label="fantasy" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#tag" />
    <category term="reviews" label="reviews" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#tag" />
    
    <content type="html" xml:lang="en" xml:base="http://blue-mage.net/blog/">
        <![CDATA[<div><a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0756403146?ie=UTF8&amp;tag=hilhom-20&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=390957&amp;creativeASIN=0756403146"><img src="Black%20Sun%20Rising.jpg" border="0" /><img alt="Black Sun Rising.jpg" src="http://blue-mage.net/blog/Pictures/Black%20Sun%20Rising.jpg" class="mt-image-left" style="margin: 0pt 20px 20px 0pt; float: left;" height="200" /></a><font style="font-size: 1.25em;"><b>In Conquest Born<br /></b></font><font style="font-size: 0.9em;"><em>C.S. Friedman</em><br /></font><br />I'd like to start by saying that I absolutely adored <a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0756400430?ie=UTF8&amp;tag=hilhom-20&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=390957&amp;creativeASIN=0756400430"><em>In Conquest Born</em></a>. It was topsy and turvy and ever so twisty. It had characters who were deep and interesting and that behaved like real (albeit rather strange) people. <i>Black Sun Rising</i> didn't. That doesn't mean it didn't try hard. And I <i>wanted</i> to like it. I'm even somewhat ashamed to admit I couldn't finish it. That's not something that happens very often.<br /><br />Gerald Tarrant certainly has the potential to be an interesting character, but nothing comes of it in the first book. He's evil and we know it. And yet, he's evil for the best possible reasons. His evilness isn't pure, though his genius certainly continues throughout. The same thing happens with Damien Vryce, the priest and Ciani, the former adept. All of them are reduced to little more than their most particular obsessions throughout the book. There is certainly a reason for it in connection with the Fae on Erna, but I really and truly need more meat on my characters.<br /><br />The Fae are the other big problem with the book. In and of itself, I really like the concept. A natural force that responds to our most powerful psychic emanations and literally modifies the environment around it totally works. While the earth, tidal and solar fae are all fine, the dark fae don't fit in at all. According to the mythos in the book, the first three are neutral but the dark fae respond to our fears. The dark fae also seem to be much more pervasive than the other three types. If she'd just managed to keep the four types balanced, it really would have made the book work - at least long enough to ignore the lack of depth in the characters.<br /><br />The rakh were a different story altogether. A species whose evolution was caused by the Fae and preciptated by humanity's arrival on Erna becomes a fascinating foil. They hate us, and with excellent reason. This was one of those instances where the concept of the Fae actually works quite well. One of the other major uses of the Fae in this first book are within the Church and this is where it turns into a liability again. Using the belief of many of their believers, the Church on Erna is able to channel greater <strike>power</strike> amounts of Fae and create what are essentially holy weapons to use against the Hunter. After spending so much time in the book emphasizing that the Fae are <i>not</i> magical, she instantly relegates them to a magical purpose.<br /><br />It may be that all of this gets better as the series goes on, but I can't be bothered to expend the energy to find out. There's just nothing here to pull me in.<br /></div>]]>
        
    </content>
</entry>

