    <summary>I finally finished the anthology Federations edited by John Joseph Adams. I&apos;m not normally one to pick up anthologies, but after such rave reviews, it&apos;s a little bit hard to argue.In short: I like. What really surprised me was that...</summary>
    <author>
        <name>Rob Hilton</name>
        
    </author>
    
        <category term="Books" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#category" />
    
    <category term="books" label="books" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#tag" />
    <category term="reviews" label="reviews" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#tag" />
    <category term="scifi" label="sci-fi" scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#tag" />
    
    <content type="html" xml:lang="en" xml:base="http://blue-mage.net/blog/">
        <![CDATA[<div><a href="http://blue-mage.net/blog/Pictures/Covers/federationsfrontcover.jpg"><img alt="federationsfrontcover.jpg" src="http://blue-mage.net/blog/assets_c/2009/08/federationsfrontcover-thumb-95x150-1.jpg" class="mt-image-left" style="margin: 0pt 20px 20px 0pt; float: left;" height="200" /></a>I finally finished the anthology <i>Federations</i> edited by John Joseph Adams. I'm not normally one to pick up anthologies, but after such <a href="http://www.tor.com/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=blog&amp;id=30214#30484">rave</a> <a href="http://io9.com/5321453/interstellar-fiction-with-a-human-perspective">reviews</a>, it's a little bit hard to argue.<br /><br />In short: I like. What really surprised me was that some of the authors
I would normally consider the strongest put some of the weakest stories
into this collection. While Anne McCaffrey's Helva story, <i>The Ship Who Returned</i> is true to the tradition of those awesome books, it does try pretty hard to tie up some of the loose ends from <i>The City Who Fought</i>. I also think she could have found a better backdrop for Helva's neurosis over Niall's death than a planet full of nuns.<br /><br />Continuing
in the tradition of neurotic heroes is Mazer Rackham who's on a light
speed round trip so that he'll still be alive to command Earth's forces
when they arrive at the Bugger worlds. Mazer has decided that he was
the victim of lucky timing and just stupid enough to ignore his orders.
For some strange reason he doesn't think those appropriate qualities in
a supreme commander. Gee, wonder why? The biggest problem is that it's
one of those single-character back-and-forth message affairs that tend
to get tiresome after a while.<br /><br />Also suffering from unexplained weakness were George R.R. Martin's <i>Warship</i> which was <i>way </i>too predictable and Robert Silverberg's <i>Symbiont</i>
which was simultaneously predictable (but in a good way) and not nearly
as exciting as it should have been. It may be worth noting that both of
those last were collaborations. <i>Life-Suspension</i> (L. E. Modesitt
Jr.) was weird and possibly pointless more than anything else. I hate a
story with an ending without resolution. I also hope that I never read
any of Harry Turtledove's "comedy" again. Maybe I'm just prejudiced
against rodent spaceship pilots, amphibians would have been much more
appropriate.<br /><br />Of course, some well-known authors are actually capable of good work (wow, that sounds snarky). Bujold's <i>Aftermaths</i>, which was included in <a href="http://www.librarything.com/work/4882289/book/34343071"><i>Cordelia's Honor</i></a>
is just the right blend of sad and mildly creepy. And Kevin J. Anderson
who is normally far from one of my personal favourites put in a really
neat story called <i>Prisons</i>. That one was really more of the
perfect blend of violence, vengeance and sadness. And just in case I'm
starting to sound incredibly depressed, Alan Dean Foster's <i>Pardon Our Conquest</i> is the perfect twist of comedy.<br /><br />Any
addition to the Coyote universe by Allen Steele is always welcome.
Colonization has never been as interesting as he manages to make it
before. It's also very cute, which is occasionally difficult to manage
on an interstellar scale. One of the Canadian sci-fi authors that I
quite enjoy is James Alan Gardner, who pulls off interstellar cuteness
on a truly impressive scale.<br /><br />Where the real strength of <i>Federations</i>
lies is in the relatively unknown authors who manage to pull rabbits
out of their literary hats. John C. Wright brings new and very literal
meaning to the term "space opera" in <i>Twilight of the Gods</i>, a space-bound and STL (albeit truncated) version of Wagner's <i>Der Ring des Nibelungen</i>. I really, really hope he writes a series based on it. I wantssss....<br /><br /><i>Swanwatch</i>
also provides a lovely touch of the East that's both musical and
poetic, neither of which is a characteristic one would normally
associate with the black holes that are at the centre of the story. <i>Esakhara</i> by Trent Hergenrader and <i>The Culture Archivist</i> by Jeremiah Tolbert also have a major cultural and anthropological bent.<br /><br />And in the end comes the end. <i>Golubash, or Wine-Blood-War Elegy</i>
by Cathrynne Valente isn't really the best science-fiction, but it
makes for an awesome ending. It's robust and flavourful without being
overwhelming, and it brings the book to an awesome close.<br /></div>


]]>
        
    </content>
</entry>

